{
  "doc_id": "38989",
  "text": "As mentioned above, the mechanism of cAMR has not been fully elucidated; hence, an established treatment guideline does not exist [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The use of tacrolimus and mycophenolate mofetil rescue therapy in cAMR does not show significant improvement in allograft function, which means that a conventional immuno- suppressant regimen cannot prevent or reverse it [CITATION_4] . Some researchers have proposed that therapies directed at the humoral immune response may be required to successfully treat cAMR, since antibody-mediated tissue injury, rather than T-cell mediated immunity, is associated with its development [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Thus far, several drugs have been introduced to suppress the various steps of humoral immune reactions, and several studies that apply these drugs for the treatment of cAMR are on-going (Fig. 2) [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] .",
